'''USS ''Philippine Sea'' (CG-58)''' is a [[Ticonderoga class cruiser|Flight II ''Ticonderoga''-class guided missile cruiser]] on active service in the [[United States Navy]].  She is named for the [[Battle of the Philippine Sea]] during [[World War II]] and is the second ship to bear the name.   She has completed multiple deployments as part of [[War in Afghanistan (2001-present)|Operation Enduring Freedom]] since 2001.

==Operational history==
In 2003, the ship was assigned to [[Carrier Strike Group Fourteen|Cruiser-Destroyer Group 12]].<ref>http://www.hazegray.org/worldnav/usa/surface.htm, accessed May 2012</ref>

In 2010, the ship failed her initial [[Board of Inspection and Survey]] (INSURV) inspection.<ref>McMichael, William "[http://www.navytimes.com/news/2010/12/navy-insurvs-122010w/ Fla. cruiser, Va. frigate flunk INSURV]", ''[[Navy Times]]'', 20 December 2010.</ref>  On 7 May 2011, ''Philippine Sea'' departed Mayport for a scheduled overseas deployment to the U.S. Fifth Fleet and U.S. Sixth Fleet Area of Responsibility.<ref name=UScarrierCG-58>{{cite web | title= USS ''Philippine Sea'' (CG-58) | url= http://www.uscarriers.net/cg58history.htm | publisher= U.S. Carriers: United States Ships (USS) history and deployments | date= 9 December 2010 | accessdate=2011-09-13}}</ref>  On 3 June 2011, ''Philippine Sea'' paid a port visit to [[Kiel, Germany]], prior to participating with the multi-national exercise Baltic Operations 2011 (BALTOPS-2011).  This exercise included naval units from the United States, Russian, Danish, Polish and French navies, and BALTOPS-2011 ended on 21 June 2011.<ref name=UScarrierCG-58/><ref>{{cite web | title= Second Phase of BALTOPS 2011 Takes Place in Baltic Sea | url= http://navaltoday.com/2011/06/13/second-phase-of-baltops-2011-takes-place-in-baltic-sea/ | publisher= NavyToday.com | date= June 2011 | accessdate=2011-09-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title= Russia: Sea Phase of BALTOPS-2011 Finishes in Baltic Sea | url= http://navaltoday.com/2011/06/21/russia-sea-phase-of-baltops-2011-finishes-in-baltic-sea/ | publisher= NavyToday.com | date= 21 June 2011 | accessdate=2011-09-13}}</ref>  On 6 July 2011, ''Philippine Sea'' rescued 26 Filipino crew members from the Marshall Islands-owned, Liberian-flagged [[supertanker]] ''[[Brilliante Virtuoso]]'' southwest of [[Aden, Yemen]], after the ship's superstructure was set on fire following a reported attack by pirates using [[rocket-propelled grenades]] (RPG).<ref name=UScarrierCG-58/><ref>{{cite web | title= USS ''Philippine Sea'' Rescues ''Brilliante Virtuoso'' Crew off Aden | url= http://www.navy.mil/search/display.asp?story_id=61448 | work= NNS110706-03 | publisher= Combined Maritime Forces Public Affairs | date= 6 July 2011 | accessdate=2011-09-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title= CMF Ship USS ''Philippine Sea'' (CG 58) rescues crew from ''Brilliante Virtuoso'' | url= http://www.cusnc.navy.mil/articles/2011/073.html | work= Release #073-11 | publisher= Combined Maritime Forces Public Affairs | date= 6 July 2011 | accessdate=2011-09-13}}</ref>  ''Philippine Sea'' transited the [[Suez Canal]] on 1 July 2011.<ref name=UScarrierCG-58/>

The cremated remains of [[Neil Armstrong]] were buried at sea from the warship on 14 September 2012, in the Atlantic Ocean.<ref>{{cite web | title= Neil Armstrong Laid to Rest in Atlantic | url= http://www.nasa.gov/topics/people/features/armstrong_cathedral_memorial.html | publisher= NASA | date= 13 September 2012 | accessdate=2012-09-14}}</ref>

[[File:Neil Armstrong burial at sea (201209140008HQ).jpg|thumb|left|Neil Armstrong's [[burial at sea]] on September 14, 2012]]

Starting on 23 September 2014 [[Tomahawk missiles]] from the ''USS Philippine Sea'' in the [[Persian Gulf]] were [[American-led coalition intervention in Syria|fired at sites]] in [[Syria]] targeting [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]]'s command-and-control centers, training camps and weapons depots. The operation was expected to last several hours, with the first explosions from Tomahawk missiles heard near [[Raqqa]] in northern Syria. The USS Philippine Sea was part of the [[USS George H.W. Bush]] carrier strike group. <ref>[http://cnsnews.com/news/article/patrick-goodenough/us-arab-partners-launch-air-attack-against-isis-targets-syria] US, Arab Partners Launch Air Attack Against ISIS Targets in Syria. Retrieved on 23 September 2014.</ref> <ref>[http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2014/09/22/us-launches-first-wave-bombing-strikes-over-syria/] US, Arab allies launch first wave of strikes in Syria. Retrieved on 23 September 2014.</ref>

